segments.text: Nicknames that you recall?
That I was called?
No, anybody.
Anybody?
That you remember.
Everybody had a nickname.
Yeah.
Normally it was, it could be ethnic origin, Greek.
We had four or five Greek Americans.
We would just call them Greek.
The rest of them were just kind of a shortened of their name.
Very few people were called by their regular name.
What about the Hispanics?
What were they called?
I don't recall.
Obviously there were the Hispanics, there was no ethnic sensitivities back in those days, but it was always with respect.
I don't remember anything really derogatory on an ethnic basis.
You know, if you call somebody a Greek or whatever, it's because he was Greek.
What about faculty nicknames?
Oh, well, all the faculty members had names.
Unless they were really good professors who had no idiosyncrasies, but as you know, as a former professor, and I've been an adjunct professor, most professors have some somewhat idiosyncratic.
But share some of those with me that you remember.
Well, Shaky Joe R. was one civil engineering professor, and that was kind of a low-class thing to call him because he had some kind of shake in his right hand there.
Shaky Joe.
My sanitary engineering professor, we called him Fecal Joe, Joe Sorrells.
Dr. Harrington was just Doc.
I don't know where he got that name, Doc Harrington.
Is that M.T.
or no?
No, no.
No, I had no relationship.
Same last name, but no relationship.
A real character.
We would normally call them by what they taught.
What about English or math or chemistry?
Well, of course, we all took about the same curriculum our freshman and sophomore year.
So those were kind of the mass.
We didn't quite get as close to professors of freshman and sophomore year as we did.
But normally in our junior and senior years in civil engineering, we'd call them by what they taught.
Concrete Bill or Steel John or Fecal Joe.
And if they had certain idiosyncrasies, we'd call them by that.
One of my favorite of that period was J.G.H.
Thompson in Emmy.
He was alphabet.
Alphabet Thompson?
I think I remember that, yeah.
All right, let's see.
We're getting near the end now.
What are the key events or traditions or practices that make up the basis for Aggie feelings, love?
Dedication.
Kind of the rallying points.
What's in the recipe there?
Well, certainly kind of the umbrella is the Association of Former Students, which is, as anybody knowledgeable knows, you know being in the Big Eight and the Big 12 at Missouri.
And I've looked at alumni organizations throughout the country because I've had the opportunity to spend a lot of time in my profession
at various universities.
And I've always made it kind of a habit to go back and look at their alumni organizations to see how it operates compared to the Association of Former Students.
And with that being braggadocio, braggadocio, there's no organization that even comes close.
All right, but why do Aggie,
alums feel that way about their school?
Well, certainly it goes back to their college experience back in those days.
I thought it would probably end when the Corps became not the dominating factor, but that hasn't really proved to be true.

I've had three daughters who've gone there, and they rallied to the same rallying points that I do, all three of whom were in sororities, and didn't really spend a lot of time dating guys in the Corps.
So, of course, they all went there as young children, so they got imbued in the scene.
But
I think your college days certainly is a great starting point.
College at any university should be a gratifying experience.

That's when you really go from somebody who's not productive, even the end product of a university, to somebody who is productive, who contributes to the GNV, contributes to the social aspects of society.
But I think A&M was special in that it had such a tradition itself, being a land grant school, being a military school, being an all-male school.
in the tradition of Virginia military, Virginia Tech, Clemson, as you mentioned earlier, gave you kind of a special status.
And I think that was the rallying point.
So people now in their 50s and 60s who had that special time in the Corps of Cadets and shared the male-dominated scene
have that special feeling.
But it's carried on after the Corps became less of a factor.
Still a major factor, but percentage-wise, the student body is much smaller, of course.
Are there any events while an Aggie is a student that are essential ingredients in this loyalty feeling?
Well, certainly the muster and certainly the football weekends, the muster, I guess, are the two biggest events.
Graduation, the commissioning.
Those things come to mind as being kind of the highlights.
Are there any physical things?
Any tangible things?
Which promotes the loyalty to the school?
You mean outside the campus?
Like what's on your face?
Oh, the Aggie ring.
Well, sure.
Aggie ring's unique.
Certainly...
When I first put on my Aggie ring, it was obvious.
I mean, you could spot them wherever you went, so when you'd notice an Aggie ring, it was immediately a point of conversation, which I have appreciated and enjoyed in all parts of the world.
On airplanes and foreign countries, when you see an Aggie ring, it's pretty obvious.
Do you remember what it cost you?
Yeah, I do.
It seemed like it was about $85.
And did that $85 come easy?
No.
Well, as I recall, the association picked up half of it.
I may have paid half of that, $45 or something.
Now, did you all have any ritual or routine of what you would do when you got the ring?
Well, there was the ring dance, of course, which you have your, in this case, my future wife.
Well, she puts the ring on under the big ring envelope there.
One ritual, which I'm not even sure, it was upside down when you were a senior, and then when you graduate, you turn it right side up.
I'm not sure if that's still a tradition or not.
I don't know either.
Today, I understand that with some of them, you're supposed to put it in a pitcher of beer and chug a lot, but y'all didn't do that.
That's something.
God forbid if you have to swallow it.
Well, apparently that has happened a couple of times.
No, there's a lot of traditions that we didn't have there, and a lot of traditions we had then that are not enjoyed today.
Let's see.
Are you at liberty to say anything about any secret fraternities?
Well, there was none there when I was there.
There was the TTs before I got there, which was kind of flushed out.
I just read about it because I had a brother in school at that time when that was a big deal.
We never had any secret fraternities at all when I was there.
That I knew about, if it were secret, they were very good secret because neither I nor my friends, many of them were student leaders and core leaders,
I didn't even hear about it.
I didn't hear about any in the 60s and 70s if they were there.
Frankly, we were too busy with core activities and our curriculum and our social life, which was pretty normal, to fool anything like that.
All right.
Only two or three more questions.
What did it, as you look back, what did it mean to you that you attended Texas A&M?
Well, it...
It was the springboard really into my profession, to my maturity, I think into good citizenship.

I guess the thing that I remember that I think was probably the biggest jumpstart by going to A&M, when I attributed all of this to the corporate edge, is that I simply didn't have time to do anything.
Every minute was occupied.
And today, see I got out in 59, so it's almost 40 years later.
I feel like I have the ability to use my time effectively in my profession in this room.
When I get in the morning, everything is programmed so that every minute, when I play, I play, but when I work, I work, and it's organized.
And I attribute that really to the fact that I just had no time, particularly as a freshman and sophomore at A&M, to do anything except my core activities and my education.
It's just a wonderful, through the accident of going to A&M at that period of time, it's a wonderful, I think, training that has served me well in my profession throughout my career.
Last question.
Yeah.
What feelings do you hold in your heart now for Texas A&M?
Well, the same as, I guess, my colleagues.
I think the taxpayers got their money's worth.
When you look at what A&M graduates have done
in society, and I'm not sure what the yardstick is.
It's probably give back to society producing a lot of the wealth of our state, giving it back unselfishly.
It's a special feeling, and it's common through all my friends.
I mean, it's an easy thing.
So it was, again, that comes at a very special time in your life when you come in as a 16- or 17-year-old.
Forget about what your IQ is or what your propensity to learning is.
You're immature.
We thought we were kind of hot shots because we had a great high school.
I had a great high school career.
And I thought I was ready for anything.
But you're not.
But when you come out of A&M, you're 21 or 22 years old.
You've got a basic education.
You understand the basic sciences.
You understand what the world's like a little bit more.
You have strong friendships which stay with you for the rest of your life.
It's a state institution.
The taxpayers pay, now it's 30% or 40% of the state taxpayers.
But the federal and the state pick up a good portion.
What they don't pay, your parents do.
But the state wants a return on that investment.
And I'd venture to say that the return on investment of A&M has probably been the best of any university in the country, state university, maybe private or public.
Again, you can't put a yardstick to that, but I'm out in society.
We've got this country right now, and I've always felt that way, that the best deal a taxpayer's ever got was sending a kid to A&M.
